course_title: SELECTED TOPICS IN SEOS: Coastal Ocean Observatory Science and Time-Series Data Analysis
subject: EOS

sections.description:
Registered students will participate in the 2018 international PICES Summer School that is jointly sponsored by PICES (North Pacific Marine Science Organization), Ocean Networks Canada and the Department of Fisheries and Oceans.  The theme for the 2018 summer school is Coastal Ocean Observatory Science. The summer school will consist of lectures, field expeditions, laboratory demonstrations of ocean sensors, and a ‘hands-on’ introduction to sensor calibration and data quality/data assurance techniques. The scope of the lectures, demonstrations and exercises will cover sensors and sampling equipment used to measure physical, biological, chemical, and biogeochemical properties of coastal waters of British Columbia. A variety of high-resolution fixed and mobile-platform time-series data-sets will form the basis of the demonstrations and hands-on exercises.
Datasets will include: deep-basin and surface measurement time series (temperature, salinity, dissolved oxygen); active acoustics (echo-sounder and acoustic Doppler current profiler); passive acoustics (hydrophones); video imagery; and biogeochemical sensors (e.g. Chlorophyll and CDOM fluorescence, and pCO2).
The curriculum will include detailed lectures from local experts, at-sea and laboratory demonstrations of sensors, and training in statistical analysis of high resolution time-series, in situ calibrations, QA/QC protocols, and automated analysis of underwater imagery. Participants will also be introduced to the Salish Sea during a mid-week field trip onboard sensor-equipped ferries that will include lectures and visits to the Vancouver Aquarium.  
Course participants will be provided with a time-series dataset on 1 June together with analytical tools and instructions for data analysis.  For this initial assignment students will be able to choose among the different datasets described above.

Pre-requisite for this course is MECH 200 and MECH350.
Students completing MECH 450C will:

1.       Gain in-depth knowledge of the product idea generation phase and product design methodologies,

2.       particularly for consumer products.

3.       Examine the design techniques specific to consumer products; for example: design for manufacture,

4.       design for assembly, product lifecycle analysis, quality management techniques, universal design,

5.       user experience design, and sustainable design.

6.       Develop in-depth knowledge about several aspects of design through a “design research” exercise,

7.       where each group will take responsibility for a specific topic(s) and present their research to the rest

8.       of the class.

9.       Mimic the activity of a design consultancy where a response to a client’s brief must be generated

10.   efficiently and rapidly.

11.   Students are expected to join the class with several ideas that are suitable for a product development

12.   exercise, and to use it as an opportunity to explore and apply the relevant product design

13.   philosophies covered in the class.

14.   Each group will complete a product design package.

15.   There will be some interaction with the Faculty of Business.

course_title: SPECIAL TOPICS: Introduction to Musculoskeletal (MSk) Biomechanics
subject: MECH

sections.description:
Pre-requisite for this course is MECH220.
MECH 450D will explore how fundamental engineering principles can be applied to the human musculoskeletal (MSk) system to solve biomechanical problems. In addition to establishing an understanding of basic MSk anatomy and nomenclature, students will study the biomechanical effects of muscle, bone, tendons, and ligaments on the overall human MSk system. Biomechanical kinematic and force analysis will also be studied using first principles and spatial transformation methods. As well, throughout the course, technologies commonly used to assess MSk biomechanical variables will be discussed. Finally, applications of these techniques to computer assisted surgery and computational MSk modelling will be introduced.
Prerequisite for this course is MECH220.

Pre-requisite for this course is MECH395.
MECH 450E introduce basic principles and application of solar energy in engineering systems mainly in the form of solar thermal and photovoltaic energy conversion. The covered topics are as follows:

1. Introduction consisting of a short introduction to solar energy followed by review of energy-related environmental problems and climate change resulting from non-renewable sources of energy.

2. Solar geometry and solar radiation heat transfer, solar radiation received by a surface at different slopes, shading, methods for estimating the amount of solar radiation received on a specific surface on the Earth both from correlation and meteorological data.

3. Solar collectors, their optical and thermal analysis for both flat plate and concentrating solar collectors as well as vacuum tube collectors with and without heat pipes. Parabolic trough collector is the most common type of concentrating collectors which is discussed in this part.

4. Analysis of collector performance through experimental methods, collector thermal efficiency, collector incidence-angle modifier and the acceptance angle for concentrating collectors.

5. Passive and active solar water-heating systems, characteristics and thermal analysis of heat storage systems for both water and air systems, module and array design methods, methods to calculate the hot-water demand.

6. Photovoltaics energy conversion starting with general characteristics of semiconductors followed by photovoltaic panels and related equipment, a review of possible applications and methods to design on-grid and off-grid photovoltaic (PV) systems, examine the concentrating PV and the hybrid photovoltaic/thermal (PV/T) systems.
